</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uanowintrueheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Anowin Trueheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Shadow Scribe</span><br>  Posts: 247<br> <font color=#8B0000>(4/4/02 10:28:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/fhordeofshadows15583frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=194.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wtf</span><hr size=1> You know I can't resist a good debate.<br>
<br>
Putting a warning label on a video game does not &quot;demean the premise of free will.&quot;  In fact, it has no bearing on free will whatsoever.  Any individual still has just as much of a right to purchase that game as he did before the label.  There have been warning labels on records for some time now, and on movies for a long long time.  I doubt they have affected anyone's free will.<br>
<br>
The sentiment here, though understandable, misses an important aspect of the law in cases like this.  The law does not look to whether or not someone had problems, or someone was &quot;not normal,&quot; or someone is predisposed to addiction -- in negligence cases, it is an objective standard, not subjective.  The only question to be answered is whether SONY knew or should have known that a reasonable person would have reacted the way this kid did.  And the answer to that, I think we would all agree, is NO.<br>
<br>
As for the labels, such a requirement would likely come from the legislative branch, not the judiciary (in the form of injunctive relief).  Without a doubt, such labels would NOT be limited to EQ -- they would apply across the board to any video game that could conceivably involve hours and hours of game play.  So don't worry kids, your EQ would be safe from the &quot;stigma&quot; of a warning label -- it would be commonplace on all video games, just like movies.<br>
<br>
In all honesty, it surprised me greatly that anyone would take this woman's case, especially given the fact that the causal chain may have been broken by several intervening causes.  However, it did not surprise me to discover that the sap who took the case is from Miami.<br>
<br>
