<br>
To further this debate with Anowin, I would ask, is not the addiction of EQ a forseeable consequence?  I wager verant has the stats of the average number of hours of game play per player, and what percent of people play more than 40 hrs a week.  Is it not forseeable that some people may get in to deep, and as such they have a responsibility to protect the consumer to some extent?  I know this is a reversal from my previous position, but Anowin got me in the spirit of the debate.<br>
<br>
As I understand negilgence, the plaintiff alleges the defendent failed to exercise due care towards persons who could reasonably be forseen to be affected by the conduct.  Can we honestly say that Sony is unaware how much people play EQ, and that for some it becomes a way of life?  Off the top of my head, I also believe that the plaintiff has to show a duty owed, that there has been a breach of that duty and that the resultant injury is due to that breach of duty.  To break it down...did verant have a duty to the deceased?, do they breach that duty by not explaining the addictive nature of EQ, and was the mans suicide a result of his addicition to EQ.<br>
<br>
In some ways, I think a jury might be swayed by the emotional arguments, and a loose legal argument can be made that might make Sony blink and settle.  That Sony knows people become addicted to EQ is without question.  The game is designed to take hours of your time, and they have the statistics and polls to determine what keeps us coming back for more.  The hardest part they will have is to make the case that EQ lead him to suicide, and not some other outside factors.  But if, EQ can be made to be a major contributing factor, things might get interesting, and with today's current witchhunts for video games, and the twisted effects of the media on our psyche's, I would be somewhat worried if I was Sony.<br>
<br>
Bara <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uanowintrueheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Anowin Trueheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Shadow Scribe</span><br>  Posts: 249<br> <font color=#8B0000>(4/5/02 11:21:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/fhordeofshadows15583frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=194.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Bara!  :)</span><hr size=1> You are pretty much there Bara.  The elements of a cause of action for negligence (which is a function of state law, so it may vary from state to state) are as follows (disclaimer: this is not legal advice in any way, shape or form, or given to further the representation of any individual.  It is just information <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  :<br>
<br>
1.  Duty - the defendant must have a legal duty to prevent harm to the Plaintiff.  With no duty, there can be no negligence.  However, the law imposes upon manufacturers a duty to exercise reasonable care so that their products in the marketplace will not harm persons or property.  SONY clearly had a duty to this young man.<br>
<br>
2.  Breach - the defendant failed to comply with the duty.  The breach here would be a failure to properly warn players that the game could cause them harm.<br>
<br>
3.  Harm - the plaintiff was harmed by the breach.  The specific harm in this case would be death, by suicide.<br>
<br>
4.  Causation - here lies the rub.  There are two types of causation in negligence cases, &quot;but for&quot; causation and proximate causation.  &quot;But for&quot; or actual causation means that &quot;but for&quot; SONY's conduct in failing to warn, the harm would not have occurred.  Obviously there is a problem here, as it would be difficult if not impossible to prove that SONY was the cause of this man acutally taking his own life.  It would be different if the packaging on the box was defective, causing someone to get a cut and bleed to death...The second prong is where foreseeability comes in.  The plaintiff must also prove proximate cause - which is concerned with whether and to what extent the defendant's conduct foreseeably and substantially caused the specific injury that actually occurred.  Once again, there is a problem, as the &quot;specific injury&quot; is not the addiction Bara, the specific injury is the death.  So the question is not whether SONY should foresee or know that EQ is addictive, it is whether SONY knew or should have known that someone could take their own life over it.<br>
<br>
The last element is damages, which is clearly satisfied.  The point is that questions of causation and breach are left to the fact finder...the jury.  So Bara has a point...if certain persons were to find causation to be satisfied, it is quite possible that SONY may be justified in being concerned.  Taking Bara's argument further, do you think that the addiction itself is &quot;bad enough&quot; to be considered an injury standing alone?<br>
<br>
Food for thought.<br>
